      "difficulty": 1,
      "overview": "Learning is more effective when study sessions are spread out over time rather than crammed into a single block.",
      "explanation": "The spacing effect is one of the most robust findings in cognitive psychology. It demonstrates that we learn and remember information more effectively when we space out our study sessions over time. For example, studying a topic for one hour on three separate days is far more effective for long-term retention than studying for three solid hours on a single dayâ€”an activity commonly known as cramming.\n\nCramming can produce a temporary feeling of mastery and may even be sufficient to pass an exam the next day. However, the knowledge fades incredibly quickly. This is because cramming primarily relies on short-term memory. Spaced practice, on the other hand, engages long-term memory consolidation. Each time you return to the material after a break, your brain is forced to work a little harder to retrieve it. This effortful retrieval, as we learned in the context of retrieval practice, signals to the brain that the information is important and should be stored more permanently.\n\nSpacing works because it allows time for forgetting to set in. This sounds counterintuitive, but a little bit of forgetting is good for long-term learning. When you revisit material you have partially forgotten, the subsequent relearning process strengthens the memory more than if you had reviewed it immediately. An ideal spacing schedule involves gradually increasing the intervals between review sessions. For instance, you might review a concept one day after learning it, then three days later, then a week later, and so on. This method directly combats the natural 'forgetting curve' and is the foundation for many popular flashcard apps like Anki.",
