      "explanation": "Interleaving is the practice of mixing different topics or problem types within a single study session, as opposed to 'blocking,' where you practice one type of problem exhaustively before moving to the next. For example, in a math study session, instead of doing 20 addition problems followed by 20 subtraction problems (blocking), an interleaved approach would mix them up throughout the session.\n\nThis method often feels more difficult and less productive in the short term. When you practice in blocks, you quickly get into a rhythm, and performance improves rapidly. This feels good, but it can be a misleading 'illusion of fluency.' You're mastering a short-term procedure, not developing a flexible understanding. Interleaving, by contrast, forces your brain to constantly switch gears. Each time you encounter a different type of problem, you must first identify what kind of problem it is and then recall the appropriate strategy or formula to solve it. This process of discriminating between problem types is a critical skill that blocking fails to develop.\n\nWhile your performance during an interleaved practice session might be lower than during a blocked session, the long-term retention and ability to apply your knowledge in new situations (known as 'transfer') are significantly higher. The struggle you experience during interleaved practice is a 'desirable difficulty.' It creates more robust and flexible memory traces. This technique is highly effective in subjects like math and science, where you need to choose the right formula, and in skill acquisition, like learning different serves in tennis or different musical scales on an instrument. By mixing it up, you're not just learning *what* to do; you're learning *when* to do it.",
