      "overview": "Combining verbal materials with visual materials to provide two distinct ways of remembering information.",
      "explanation": "Dual coding theory, proposed by Allan Paivio, suggests that our minds process information through two distinct but interconnected channels: a verbal channel (for language) and a non-verbal/visual channel (for images). The theory posits that learning and memory are enhanced when we present information using both channels simultaneously. When you combine words with a relevant image, you are creating two different memory traces for the same concept, giving you two ways to retrieve it later.\n\nFor example, if you are learning about the process of photosynthesis, reading a text description engages the verbal channel. If you also look at a clear, explanatory diagram of photosynthesis, you engage the visual channel. The combination of the two is more powerful than either one alone. The text explains the details, while the diagram shows the relationships between the parts (sunlight, water, CO2, chloroplasts, etc.) in a way that words cannot easily convey. This creates a richer, more integrated mental model of the process.\n\nIt's crucial that the visuals are meaningful and directly support the text. Simply adding decorative clip art or irrelevant photos to a presentation does not count as effective dual coding and can actually be distracting. The goal is to use visuals to organize, clarify, and reinforce the verbal information. Good examples of dual coding in practice include:\n*   Creating diagrams or flowcharts to represent a process.\n*   Drawing timelines for historical events.\n*   Using infographics with icons and charts to explain data.\n*   Sketching a quick drawing in your notes next to a key concept.\n\nBy leveraging both verbal and visual pathways, you can reduce cognitive load and build stronger, more easily retrievable memories.",
