      "explanation": "Our brains are naturally better at grasping and remembering concrete information than abstract ideas. An abstract principle, like 'the availability heuristic,' can be difficult to understand and recall on its own. However, if it's linked to a concrete exampleâ€”such as, 'After seeing several news reports about shark attacks, you start to believe they are much more common than they actually are'â€”the concept becomes immediately clearer and more memorable.\n\nUsing concrete examples is a powerful learning strategy because it grounds abstract rules in specific, real-world contexts. It works hand-in-hand with elaboration, helping you connect new ideas to your existing knowledge base. When you encounter a new abstract concept, you should actively seek out or create multiple, varied examples to illustrate it. This does two things: First, it helps you truly understand the boundaries and nuances of the concept. Second, it gives your brain more retrieval cues. Later, when you need to recall the abstract principle, you might first remember one of the concrete examples, which then triggers the abstract idea itself.\n\nTo apply this strategy, don't just rely on the examples given in a textbook. A crucial step is to generate your own examples. This act of creation forces you to engage with the material on a deeper level and serves as a powerful self-test of your understanding. If you can't create a new, accurate example of a concept, you probably don't understand it as well as you think you do. For instance, if you're learning about 'interleaving,' you could try to come up with an example from sports (practicing serves, forehands, and backhands mixed together) and another from music (practicing scales, chords, and arpeggios in a mixed sequence).",
